properties.GAR_Descri:
On 12th July 2017, a 5,818 km2 section of floating ice broke free from the Larsen C Ice Shelf in Subarea 48.5. UK scientists have examined the available data on the extent of the newly exposed marine area, and in accordance with Conservation Measure 24-04 (2016), propose that this area is designated as a Special Area for Scientific Study.

The calved area is now known as iceberg A68. The area of ice loss is equivalent to 12.12% of the baseline (pre-calving) extent of the Larsen C Ice Shelf (48,001 km2), thus meeting the criteria for designation of a Special Area for Scientific Study set out in CM 24-04, paragraph 2.

The perimeter of iceberg A68 at the time of calving (12th July 2017) is used to define the boundary of the proposed Stage 1 Special Area. This has been determined using an image acquired on 12th July 2017 by the European Copernicus Sentinel-1 satellite (Figure 2).
